  "timeframe": "1D",
  "market_context": "Gold approached the all-time high resistance at ~2070 (later clarified as ~2386 in chart scale), with multiple attempts to break above in 2020, March 2022, and May 2023. Each attempt showed strong initial momentum but failed due to weak closes, long wicks, and lack of confirmation.",
  "key_observation": "The analyst highlighted that despite strong momentum candles pushing price into resistance, breakouts failed because candles did not close above 2070, exhibited large upper wicks, and lacked volume/price action confirmation—even when volume increased during reversal.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the resistance level at ~2070 (later shown as ~2386 on chart) as a clearly visible, multi-year all-time high from August 2020, retested in March 2022 and May 2023.",
    "Step 2: Analyzed the first breakout attempt: a strong bullish momentum candle reached the level but did not close above it, failing the basic breakout criterion.",
    "Step 3: Examined the second attempt: an extreme candle with massive upper wick above resistance, then sharp reversal—showing decreased momentum and bearish shift despite high volume.",
    "Step 4: Noted that increased volume during reversal (not during upward move) worsened the failure signal, contradicting true breakout behavior.",
    "Step 5: Checked for price action confirmation and found none—no bullish engulfing, hammer, or other reversal patterns at the level.",
    "Step 6: Observed a third attempt with no momentum increase, no close above level, no volume surge, and no price action confirmation—four out of five failure signs present.",
    "Step 7: Contrasted failed attempts with the eventual successful breakout later on the right side of the chart, which featured strong momentum, solid close above resistance, and confirmation."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "A valid breakout requires not just price touching resistance, but a strong close above, increasing momentum, volume confirmation, and supporting price action. False breakouts often show long wicks, weak closes, and reversal on high volume—these are high-probability fade opportunities.",
